<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
COLORADO; 
</P>
<P>
ASPEN FUR BAN PLAN GOES TO THE VOTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A record voter turnout is possible in the swanky ski town of Aspen today for a 
referendum on proposals to ban the sale of fur and cut the size of a proposed 
$80-million hotel. 
</P>
<P>
Kathy Strickland, deputy city clerk, said she expects the two issues to draw 
out a large majority of the resort's 3,739 registered voters. If approved, the 
fur ban pushed by Mayor Bill Stirling would prohibit the sale of wild-animal 
furs, which would shut down the town's four fur-clothing stores. Opponents of 
the proposed Ritz-Carlton Hotel at the foot of Aspen Mountain want the 292-room 
hotel cut in size by one-third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
