<P>
BULGARIA REJECTS FORMER KING'S OFFER TO COME BACK FROM EXILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SOFIA, Bulgaria 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Communist government today rejected an offer by Bulgaria's former king to 
return from exile and help rebuild the country, suggesting the monarch should 
mind his own business. 
</P>
<P>
"There is no room for the revival of monarchist ideas in Bulgaria's public 
life," the government said in a statement carried by the Communist Party 
newspaper Rabotnichesko Delo. 
</P>
<P>
The statement rejected former King Simeon II's offer to use his international 
business and political connections to help revitalize Bulgaria's economy. 
</P>
<P>
It said the proposals are "strange and absolutely unacceptable, as are the 
attempts to advise the Bulgarian people about the way they should manage their 
affairs." 
</P>
<P>
Simeon II, who as a child briefly served as Bulgaria's last monarch before 
being exiled in 1946, made the proposals in an interview broadcast Sunday night 
on state television. 
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented television appearance from his home in Madrid gave many 
Bulgarians their first glimpse of the 53-year-old former king, who was forced 
to leave the country at age 9 when the Communists seized power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
