<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: MONEY CAN'T BUY LOVE -- JUST ASK SALLY AND AGA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE AGAS go gaga! Remember Sally Croker Poole, the beautiful former model who 
became the wife of the fabulously rich Aga Kahn, spiritual leader of 12 million 
Ismaeli Muslims, 20 years ago? Now all of Europe is abuzz with the story that 
Sally and the Aga Kahn are on the verge of divorce. 
</P>
<P>
The Begum, once regarded as one of the most beautiful women in the world, spent 
her recent 50th birthday alone in Switzerland. Her three children, ages 19, 18 
and 15, are in school or traveling. As for the Aga, he spends his time, as he 
has for the past five years, with gorgeous Pilar Goess, a 32-year-old Austrian 
model. The Aga sees his wife only when he must make an official appearance 
before his followers. 
</P>
<P>
It is expected there will be a quiet divorce in the not-too-distant future. 
Whether Pilar, who sports a $1-million pink diamond on her left hand, will 
become the next Begum, is anyone's guess. 
</P>
<P>
BRYANT GUMBEL of the "Today" show is certainly stepping out into public life. 
Last week he appeared at the big Council of Fashion Designers fashion tribute 
in New York and gave out an award. Now comes word that Bryant will be master of 
ceremonies on June 2, when the Friars Clubs pay tribute to Diana Ross as 
Entertainer of the Year. This event happens at the Waldorf Astoria in New York, 
and the lure of Ross is expected to pack the place to the rafters. The occasion 
will also mark the 85th anniversary of the New York Friars Club. 
</P>
<P>
MICHAEL WINNER, the director, persuaded that wonderful British actor John 
Cleese to put in an unbilled guest appearance in Winner's upcoming "Bullseye," 
which stars Michael Caine and Roger Moore. He came upon Cleese quite 
unexpectedly in Barbados, where "Bullseye" was wrapping production and where 
Cleese vacations every year. I guess basking in the sun on the beach in 
Barbados lowers an actor's resistance. 
</P>
<P>
ADVANCE WORD on "State of Grace," Phil Joanou's movie based on the Westies gang 
and Gambino family, is that the film will hit very close to home and pull no 
punches in its shocking tale of murder and terror in New York's Hell's Kitchen. 
</P>
<P>
The movie has a knockout cast that includes Ed Harris, Gary Oldman and Sean 
Penn. "State of Grace," which filmed in New York City under unusually tight 
security, opens this summer. 
</P>
<P>
PERHAPS LESLEY-ANNE Down won't be able to lift "Dallas" back to its glory days 
of ratings supremacy, but for now, at least, the British beauty is adding some 
much needed spice and glamour to the granddaddy of nighttime soaps. Down looks 
ravishing -- better than she has for some time -- and she's quite effective 
playing a high-powered PR woman. She comes off like a softer version of Joan 
Collins. 
</P>
<P>
And "Dallas" has more good news. They've invited the divine Alexis Smith back 
to reprise her role as that very soigne madwoman, Lady Jessica. (She kidnaped 
and attempted to murder Miss Ellie a few seasons back.) Well, maybe "Dallas" 
will make a ratings comeback, now that it has all this delicious womanpower 
behind it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Bryant Gumbel 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
